Date:  23/8/1862
Source:  Otago Witness
Author:
Vol / Page:  8
Edition:
Quote:  ... the most important feature is, the state of destitution to which a variety of causes have reduced most of the unsettled or King tribes in this neighbourhood. ... This state of things may be distinctly traced to the King movement itself, because there is little doubt that the constant excitement produced by the arrangements for this new government ... formed a complete bar to their settling down to any steady or useful work; while on the other hand, their constant feeling of antagonism to the British government, made the cultivation of their lands appear almost a waste of time, when a war might at any moment destroy all the results.
Notes:

